### Quick Overview

- **Purpose**: Create modals, confirmation boxes, alerts, inspectors, or popups.
- **Modal** (`showModal()`): Blocks interaction with the rest of the page + shows backdrop.
- **Non-modal** (`show()`): Allows interaction with background content.

### Key Attributes

| Attribute     | Description                                      | Notes |
|---------------|--------------------------------------------------|-------|
| `open`        | Makes dialog visible                             | Not recommended for dynamic control (use JS methods instead) |
| `closedby`    | Controls how dialog can be closed                | `any` (default light dismiss), `closerequest`, `none` |

### Most Important JavaScript API

| Method / Property          | What it does                                          | Best Use |
|---------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|----------|
| `dialog.showModal()`      | Opens as **modal** (with backdrop + focus trap)       | Most common (confirmations, forms) |
| `dialog.show()`           | Opens as **non-modal**                                | Tooltips, side panels |
| `dialog.close(returnValue)` | Closes dialog, optionally passes a value            | `dialog.close("confirmed")` |
| `dialog.returnValue`      | Gets the value passed when closed                     | Read after `'close'` event |
| `dialog.open`             | Read-only boolean (is dialog open?)                   | Check state |

**Event:**
- `'close'` — Fired when dialog is closed (via button, Esc, or `close()`).

### Practical Code Examples

**1. Basic Modal with Form (Recommended)**

```html
<button id="openBtn">Delete Account</button>

<dialog id="confirmDialog">
  <h2>Are you sure?</h2>
  <p>This action cannot be undone.</p>
  
  <form method="dialog">
    <button value="cancel">Cancel</button>
    <button value="delete">Yes, Delete</button>
  </form>
</dialog>

<script>
  const dialog = document.getElementById('confirmDialog');
  const openBtn = document.getElementById('openBtn');

  openBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    dialog.showModal();
  });

  dialog.addEventListener('close', () => {
    console.log('User chose:', dialog.returnValue);
    if (dialog.returnValue === 'delete') {
      // perform delete
    }
  });
</script>
```

**2. Styling (Very Important)**

```css
dialog {
  border: none;
  border-radius: 12px;
  padding: 2rem;
  box-shadow: 0 10px 40px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25);
  max-width: 420px;
  width: 90%;
  font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
}

dialog::backdrop {
  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.65);
  backdrop-filter: blur(6px);
}
```

### Best Practices (2026)

- Always use `showModal()` for important actions (better UX + accessibility).
- Provide an explicit close button — don’t rely only on Esc key.
- Use `autofocus` on the most important element inside the dialog (e.g., primary button or heading).
- Use `<form method="dialog">` inside dialog for easy closing with return values.
- Style `::backdrop` for a nice overlay effect.
- Never put `tabindex` on `<dialog>` itself.
- Test keyboard navigation and screen readers.

### Common Use Cases
- Confirmation dialogs (delete, logout)
- Login / signup forms in modal
- Settings panels
- Image previews or inspectors
- Alert messages

**Warning**:  
Do **not** toggle the `open` attribute manually for dynamic dialogs. Always use `.showModal()` or `.show()`.

